# TypeScript Conventions

## Exhaustive Switches with assertNever

Every switch over a union type must have a default case with `assertNever` for compile-time safety:

```typescript
import { assertNever } from '../core/types'

function getTypeColor(type: JsonNodeType): string {
  switch (type) {
    case 'string':  return 'text-accent-green'
    case 'number':  return 'text-accent-blue'
    case 'boolean': return 'text-accent-peach'
    case 'null':    return 'text-text-faint'
    case 'object':  return 'text-accent-mauve'
    case 'array':   return 'text-accent-yellow'
    default:        return assertNever(type)
  }
}
```

## Use `satisfies` for Config Objects

Validate config objects while keeping literal types:

```typescript
const typeLabels = {
  string: 'String',
  number: 'Number',
} satisfies Record<JsonNodeType, string>
```

## Avoid Non-Null Assertions

Use proper null checks instead of `!`:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const node = parseResult!.nodes.get(id)!

// ✅ GOOD
const node = parseResult?.nodes.get(id)
if (!node) return
```

## Type Definitions

- Define types in `src/core/types.ts` for shared types.
- Don't duplicate type definitions across files.
- Prefer interfaces over type aliases for object shapes.
- Use discriminated unions for state variants.
